      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/sqa-mrl5-criteria",
      "rationale": "The CFD solver (ANSYS Fluent 2024R1) is qualified under an ISO 9001:2015-certified QMS. A software validation plan, version-controlled configuration management record, and independent code audit report are on file. All simulation scripts are stored in a Git repository with signed commits, automated regression test suite (>200 test cases), and traceable change history. SQA level 5 achieved: full lifecycle documentation, independent verification of solver build, and formal deviation management process demonstrated."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 5,
      "achievedLevel": 5,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/code-verification-mrl5-criteria",
      "rationale": "Numerical code verification performed via Method of Manufactured Solutions (MMS) for all governing equation terms: continuity, momentum (RANS k-omega SST), and scalar hemolysis transport. Observed order of accuracy matches theoretical order (p_obs = 1.97 ± 0.04 vs. p_theoretical = 2.0 for second-order scheme) across three systematically refined grids. Results documented in formal code verification report with independent review sign-off."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 5,
      "achievedLevel": 5,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/discretization-error-mrl5-criteria",
      "rationale": "Grid convergence study performed on three systematically refined meshes (coarse: 4.2M, medium: 12.6M, fine: 37.8M cells; refinement ratio r=1.5). Grid Convergence Index (GCI) computed per Roache methodology. GCI_fine for NIH QoI = 1.3%, well within the 5% acceptance threshold. Temporal convergence verified: time-step refinement by factor 2 changes NIH by < 0.4%. All production simulations use fine mesh with GCI correction applied."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 5,
      "achievedLevel": 5,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/test-conditions-mrl5-criteria",
      "rationale": "Experimental test conditions for both PIV and hemolysis bench studies are fully characterised and traceable to calibrated measurement standards. Inlet flow rate measured with Coriolis mass flowmeter (±0.2% FS, NIST-traceable calibration). Rotor speed measured with optical tachometer (±1 RPM). Blood analogue viscosity characterised via cone-and-plate rheometry at test temperature (37°C ± 0.2°C). All 8 operating points replicated in triplicate; inter-run coefficient of variation < 3% for NIH. Test conditions documented in a formal test plan with independent witness sign-off."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 5,
      "achievedLevel": 5,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/output-comparison-mrl5-criteria",
      "rationale": "Quantitative output comparison performed using multiple metrics: (1) NIH ratio (predicted/measured) within 1.15 for all 8 operating points; (2) Bland-Altman 95% limits of agreement: −0.003 to +0.008 g/100L, no proportional bias detected; (3) Lin's concordance correlation coefficient CCC = 0.984 (95% CI: 0.971–0.992); (4) Velocity field RMSE < 4% of bulk velocity across all PIV measurement planes. Comparison methodology pre-registered in the validation plan prior to data unblinding."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 5,
      "achievedLevel": 5,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/qoi-relevance-mrl5-criteria",
      "rationale": "The primary QoI (NIH, g/100L) is directly mapped to the clinical endpoint (plasma-free haemoglobin elevation) and the regulatory acceptance criterion (NIH < 0.01 g/100L per FDA guidance). A formal QoI traceability matrix links each simulation output to the corresponding clinical risk, regulatory requirement, and validation measurement. Secondary QoIs (wall shear stress distribution, exposure time histogram) are documented as supporting evidence. QoI relevance reviewed and approved by a clinical subject matter expert."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 5,
      "achievedLevel": 5,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/validation-relevance-mrl5-criteria",
      "rationale": "Validation activities are conducted under conditions that closely match the COU: same pump geometry (FDA generic centrifugal pump), same blood analogue fluid (glycerol-water, matched viscosity and density), overlapping flow-speed envelope (2–6 L/min, 2000–3500 RPM), and same hemolysis power-law damage model. A validation relevance matrix scores each validation experiment against 9 COU attributes; all scores ≥ 4/5. Gaps between validation conditions and COU (e.g., in vivo blood rheology vs. Newtonian analogue) are explicitly documented with bounding sensitivity analyses demonstrating < 8% impact on NIH."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 5,
      "achievedLevel": 5,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/solver-error-mrl5-criteria",
      "rationale": "Iterative convergence verified by monitoring residuals (< 10^-6 for all equations) and QoI stabilisation (< 0.1% change over final 500 iterations). Round-off error assessed via double-precision arithmetic throughout; mixed-precision sensitivity study confirms < 0.05% impact on NIH. Solver settings (relaxation factors, discretisation schemes) documented and locked in version-controlled parameter file. Independent re-run on different HPC cluster (different compiler, MPI implementation) reproduces NIH within 0.3%, confirming platform independence."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 5,
      "achievedLevel": 5,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/use-error-mrl5-criteria",
      "rationale": "Use error risk assessed via a structured FMEA of the simulation workflow (geometry import, meshing, boundary condition assignment, post-processing). All high-risk steps (BC assignment, hemolysis model parameter entry) are subject to independent peer review using a formal checklist. Automated pre-processing scripts with input validation reduce manual transcription errors. A simulation execution log is auto-generated and archived for each run. Two independent analysts reproduced NIH results within 0.5% following the documented workflow, confirming procedural robustness."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 5,
      "achievedLevel": 5,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/model-form-mrl5-criteria",
      "rationale": "Model form uncertainty assessed through systematic comparison of three turbulence models (k-omega SST, realizable k-epsilon, RSM) and two hemolysis damage models (Giersiepen-Wurzinger power law, Farinas modified). k-omega SST with Farinas model selected based on best agreement with experimental data (lowest RMSE across all validation cases). Model form uncertainty contribution to NIH quantified at ±9% (95% CI) via Bayesian model averaging across the candidate set. This uncertainty is propagated into the final UQ budget and does not alter the accept/reject decision."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 5,
      "achievedLevel": 5,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/model-inputs-mrl5-criteria",
      "rationale": "All 11 model inputs characterised with probability distributions derived from measurement data or literature meta-analysis: inlet velocity profile (Womersley, measured), blood viscosity (log-normal, 8 rheometry measurements), rotor speed (normal, tachometer data), gap clearance (uniform, manufacturing tolerance specification), hemolysis model coefficients (multivariate normal, posterior from Bayesian calibration against 24 independent datasets). Input correlations assessed; rotor speed and flow rate correlation (r=0.12) included in UQ propagation. Full input characterisation report with traceability to primary data sources on file."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 5,
      "achievedLevel": 5,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/test-samples-mrl5-criteria",
      "rationale": "Validation experiments used fresh ovine blood (within 6 hours of collection) from 6 individual donors, providing biological variability representative of the patient population. Blood characterised for haematocrit (40±2%), MCV, and baseline plasma-free haemoglobin prior to each test. Pump wetted surfaces manufactured from the same material lot as the clinical device (medical-grade titanium). Sample preparation, handling, and storage protocols follow ASTM F1841 and are documented in a formal test protocol with IQ/OQ/PQ records. Statistical power analysis confirmed n=6 donors provides 80% power to detect a 15% difference in NIH at α=0.05."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 5,
      "achievedLevel": 5,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/input-equivalency-mrl5-criteria",
      "rationale": "Equivalency between simulation input parameters and experimental conditions formally assessed via a parameter equivalency matrix covering all 11 uncertain inputs. For each parameter, the simulation input distribution is compared against the measured experimental distribution using a two-sample Kolmogorov-Smirnov test (all p > 0.15, no significant difference). Non-Newtonian blood rheology in the COU vs. Newtonian analogue in validation is the largest identified gap; a bounding non-Newtonian sensitivity study (Carreau-Yasuda model) shows < 6% impact on NIH, within the accepted model uncertainty budget. Equivalency assessment reviewed and approved by an independent technical reviewer."
    }
